The paper focuses on saliency and attribution methods in deep neural networks, which are commonly used in computer vision tasks such as image classification and object detection. Therefore, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes a meta-learning approach, which falls under the scope of cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of perturbation masks, which is a common technique in adversarial attacks, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning) another likely sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of activations and gradients, which are commonly used in natural language processing tasks, making cs.CL (Computation and Language) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the computation of gradients, which is a fundamental concept in neural networks, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category as well.
